Introduction¶

The National Football League, also known as the NFL, was established in 1920 and made in the United States. Althogh it was created more than 100 years ago, a lot of the modern stats that we have today weren't recored. Some of the more important stats that I'm looking at pertain to the Quarterback position in the NFL. I got the NFL Statistics dataset from Kaggle.com.This data was collected on NFL.com and put into a dataset. The dataset looks at specific game logs from the NFL and focuses on the QBs' stats in that game. Originally, this dataset included 40,247 games from the years 1970-2016. This dataset wasn't perfect for me to use as is, so I had to do a lot of data wrangling to make sure all of the data was in a specific form in order for me to run tests and answer my questions to my best ability. One of the major challenges that I faced was making sure all of the data was in a certain format that would allow me to run all of my models and find the answers to my questions. Converting the dataset from kaggle to jupyterhub is a challenge in itself because of the differences between the two. I had to do things like change the names of the columns, change the datatypes of the columns, and drop some of the values that weren't needed.

In these two notebooks, I will be exploring and answering some of the questions that I had initally when I was looking at the dataset. The questions include: Is there a significant correlation between the year and number of passes? Is there a significat correlation between Passer Rating and Week that the QB played? Can I predict the Passer Rating? Is the win column based on a QBs qbr (can we predict the W/L column using the qbr)? All of these questions are related. They will allow me to understand how important quarterbacks are to their team.

Gillies, Kendall. NFL Statistics. Kaggle, 9 June 2017, www.kaggle.com/datasets/kendallgillies/nflstatistics/.

Correlation Hypothesis Test¶

Question 1:¶

Is there a significant correlation between the year and number of passes?¶

I wanted to ask this question because a lot of fans of the NFL say that running backs aren't as important as they used to be. In return, their claim is that as the years go on, the league has been passing a lot more then they used to be. I wanted to test this to see if there was a significant correlation between the year of the game and the the number of passes in said game. To do this I will be using the Year column and the Passes_Attempted column. This would give me an idea if they were passing more or not as the year go on. If the correlation is significant, then according to my dataset, it would prove that as the years go on, the NFL is passing the ball more. It is importnat to keep in mind that this would only answer the question for my specific dataset, and this doesn't mean that it is the same for the whole National Fooball League and its history. My dataset is only from 1991-2016. In addition, this would alow me to use this as a predictor in my other models if I needed to.

With this correlation test I will be comparing permutations to the observed correlation of my dataset. This will alow me to see if there is a significant difference using the p-value. With this being said, I will need to define my null hypothesis and my alternative hypothesis.

Null hypothesis: obs_corr = 0 Alternate hypothesis = obs_corr > 0

My null hypotheis is that my observed correlation is equal to zero. This would mean that there is no correlation between the number of passes and the year of the attempted passes. My alternative hypotheis is that the observed correlation is greater than 0. This would mean that there is a correlation between the year and number of passes. My hypothesis is one tailed, meaning that I am only testing in one direction. That direction being that the observed correlation is positive. I made it this way because as you can see below, the correlation between the two is postive, so I wanted to test in the positive direction.

def simulate_correlation(df,var1,var2):
    shuffled = df[var1].sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
    corr = shuffled.corr(df[var2])
    return corr

P-Value¶

In [26]:
p_value = np.mean(corr_perms > obs_corr)
p_value
Out[26]:
0.3156

This is our p-value. The p-value shows how much of the data is greater than the observed correlations.We want our p-value to be less than .05. Essentially, we want our p-value to be 5% and that means that we are 95% confident. The p-value shows how much of the data is greater than the observed correlations. Since our alternative hypothesis showed that we were looking for the observed correlaion to be more than zero, we look at all the permutations that are greater than the observed correlation. In this case our p_value was higher than what we were expecting. This means that we will accept our null hypothesis becuase the correlation is not significant enough for us to reject it.

Overall, this data shows us that the correlation between the Year column and the Passes_Attempted columnn is not signifcant. This answers our quesion and tells us that QB's are not passing more much more as the years go on.

Question 2:¶

Is there a significant correlation between Passer Rating and Week that the QB played?¶

(Does the QB get better, worse, or stay the same as the season goes on? And if so, is there a significant correlation?)¶

I wanted to ask this question becuase it would be interesting to see if quarterbacks get better as the weeks go on or if they regress as the season go on. It would make sense if the quarterbacks get better as the weeks go on because usually players learn from their mistakes and improve. I chose to look at the passer rating in particular because this is a good way of indicating how well a quarterback is doing. The passer rating takes into account some of the passing stats and puts it into an equation. The output of this equation ranges from 0-158.3, O being bad and 158.3 being perfect. I decided to use a correlation hypothesis test because the question is dealing with two specific variables that may or may not a have a correlation. In order to see if that correlation is significant or not, I will have to test it and this is the best way to do so.

With this correlation test I will be comparing permutations to the observed correlation between week and the passer rating of my dataset. This will allow me to see if there is a significant difference between the permutations and the observed correlation using the p-value. With this being said, I will need to define my null hypothesis and my alternative hypothesis.

Null hypothesis: obs_corr = 0 Alternate hypothesis = obs_corr < 0

My null hypotheis is that my observed correlation is equal to zero. This would mean that there is no correlation between the passer rating and the week. My alternative hypotheis is that the observed correlation is less than 0. This would mean that there is a correlation between the year and number of passes. My hypothesis is one tailed, meaning that I am only testing in one direction. That direction being that the observed correlation is negative. I made it this way because as you can see below, the correlation between the two is negative, so I wanted to test in the positive direction.

Observed correlation¶

The correlation is again pretty low. It is negative which means they have a slightly inverse relationship, so as one goes up the other goes downn. We would want the coefficient to be around .7 or so for us to think that it is on the higher end of the correlation spectruem. Since it is so low we are more likely to think that the correlation is not significant, but we need to test it to make sure.

Question 3¶

Can I predict the Passer Rating?¶

I wanted to see what goes into passer rating and what some of the important factors are in order to produce this stat. For this I knew that I needed to use a numerical model. I went through trial and error and found that Knn was the best model for this specific situation. This model would also help me find out what the good predictors would be for my next model too becuase passer rating is directly related to the QB's performance.

The target here is the passer rating of the QB. I decidced to use passing yards, compeltion percentage, touchdown passes, interceptions, passing yards per attempts, and sacks as my predictors. All of these are some of the main stats for a quarterback, so they proved to be good predictors for this particular model.

Here we are making our model. We have to set our predictors and targets to variables and then split the data. After we split the data we have to stardardize it and fit it to scale. This makes it so that each variable contributes to the model equally. For example, if you are looking at the nearest neighbor to a passing yards point it will likely farther away than the nearest neighbor of an interception point because one is measuring yards and the other is measuring a turnover. Standardizing the data allows for all of the data to have a similar contribution. After we standardize the data we then fit the KNN regressor adn choose a good value for the K. In this case our k is represented by n_neighbors and I chose 5.
